The M16 fix had to be end-to-end because the OAuth “provider” value crosses five different boundaries:

1. user selects an aliased provider in the UI;
2. the v2 SDK has to type that parameter;
3. the v2 SDK has to serialize it onto the actual HTTP request correctly;
4. the server route has to resolve/remember the alias, not just the canonical provider;
5. the OAuth callback has to save the resulting credentials under the alias that the rest of opencode will later look up.

If any one layer still collapses the alias back to the canonical provider ID, the OAuth flow may appear to start, but the token ends up missing, rejected, or saved under the wrong key.

